node.text:
The Americans with Disabilities Act (ADA) turns 31 today. To mark the anniversary of this landmark law, we're spotlighting this video we made with @AccessibleTravelNYC in 2019. ⁠⁠
⁠⁠
ID: In this video, Lakshmee Lachhman-Persad, founder of the website Accessible Travel NYC, highlights sightseeing in NYC for wheelchair users. Lakshmee accompanies her sister, Annie, a wheelchair user, around NYC along with their family, and explains how they get around and navigate a day out in the City.⁠⁠
⁠⁠
For more on accessible travel in NYC, visit nycgo.com/accessibility (link in bio).

#ADA31 #ADA #AccessibleNYC

node.title: How to Explore NYC with a Wheelchair

node.text:
This is the first episode of our new video series, "The Freedom To Be." It focuses on the Black surf community in the Rockaways, with perspectives on the experience from author and former journalist Diane Cardwell (@diane_cardwell), as well as Lou Harris, the CEO of the NYC chapter of the Black Surfing Association (@black_surfing_rockaway). 
⁠⁠
About "The Freedom To Be": This series is part of #TheBlackExperienceInNYC travel hub on NYCgo.com and highlights NYC's endless and often unexpected opportunities for Black subcultures and affinity groups—acknowledging the five boroughs' vibrant abundance of ideas and expressions. A celebration of the diversity within Black culture in NYC, #TheFreedomToBe also underscores the contributions of these communities and groups to NYC's dynamism.⁠⁠
⁠⁠
Visit nycgo.com/theblackexperience for more (link in bio).⁠⁠
⁠⁠

It’s finally time to experience the five boroughs in real life again. #ItsTimeForNYC. ⁠⁠⁠⁠⁠

We've asked locals and New York City businesses and organizations to highlight their NYC itineraries this summer. Link in bio for Art, Antiques, and Bakeries from NY Forever, a non-profit dedicated to creating a stronger future for all New Yorkers⁠⁠.⁠⁠

NY Forever's latest collaboration is the Summer Camp Project, a fundraising effort with the YMCA of Greater New York to provide summer day camp scholarships to New York City kids from underserved families from across every borough during the summer of 2021. One-hundred percent of the net proceeds from NY Forever X @YMCANYC merch, designed by @ReedArtDepartment (swipe through), will go to the project. Visit nyforever.nyc/merchandise⁠⁠
⁠⁠⁠⁠⁠⁠⁠
Pictured: 1. NY Forever's streetpole banners along Flatbush Avenue in Downtown Brooklyn, with Barclays Center in the background; 2. Two models wear T-shirts and bucket hats from the NY Forever X YMCA Summer Camp Project collection; 3. A close-up of one of NY Forever's streetpole banners with the skyline of Downtown Brooklyn in the background. 📷: courtesy of @NYForever⁠⁠

node.text:
@HarlemWeek kicks off today, which presents a good opportunity to re-up our Weekend Guide to Black-Owned #Harlem by @kingronthedon, part of #TheBlackExperienceInNYC travel hub we debuted on NYCgo.com earlier this year.⁠⁠
⁠⁠
Swipe through to see the following photos—link in bio for more on the website!
⁠⁠
1. Along Convent Avenue in Sugar Hill you’ll find tree-lined streets with traditional brownstones and historic churches. 📷: Molly Flores (@am_i_rite_ladies_)⁠⁠
⁠⁠
2. Generations of celebrated musicians jump-started their careers and made their names at the Apollo Theater, pictured here. 📷: @KrisGraves⁠⁠
⁠⁠
3. Take in scenic areas such as historic Strivers’ Row two blocks of rowhouses, some of which are pictured here, that date back to the 1890s. 📷: @KrisGraves ⁠⁠
⁠⁠
4. If you’re looking for lunch, the bold color palette of Lolo’s Seafood Shack may catch your eye and lure you in. Pictured here are crab legs and corn on the cob. (Note: Lolo's is now participating in #NYCRestaurantWeek) 📷: @LolosShacks ⁠⁠
⁠⁠
5. The Schomburg Center, whose exterior is pictured here, speaks to Harlem’s pivotal role in past and present culture, with decades of contributions from Black visionaries and activists. 📷: @KrisGraves⁠⁠
⁠⁠
6. Kente Royal Gallery, whose exterior is shown here during a gallery night last year, honors the concept of sankofa, which urges Black people removed from Africa to return, reconnect, and use the experience to propel themselves and their communities forward. 📷: @kente_royal_gallery⁠⁠
⁠⁠
7. Calabar Imports sells African fashion, accessories, home goods, and gift items. Pictured here is a close-up of earrings painted with the raise fist of the Black power salute. 📷: Laylah Amatullah Barrayn (@laylahb)⁠⁠
⁠⁠
⁠⁠

If you've seen our #ItsTimeForNYC TV commercial, you may have spied none other than A$AP Ferg toward the end, welcoming visitors back to New York City.⁠⁠
⁠⁠
He's just one of several locals we asked to tell us how they're spending time in New York right now. Link in bio for @ASAPFerg's Best Eats and Iconic Haunts on NYCgo.com.⁠⁠⁠
⁠⁠⁠
You can save Ferg's itinerary or create one of your own. And when you do, you can enter our sweepstakes for a chance to experience it in real life, plus a free trip for you and a friend.*⁠⁠⁠⁠
⁠⁠⁠
Pictured: Our video, set to Chic's legendary "Good Times," features scenes of people enjoying activities throughout NYC's five boroughs. The cover photo for the video/still frame in this post features A$AP Ferg pictured with Harlem restaurateur Melba Wilson outside her namesake restaurant @MelbasHarlem ⁠⁠
⁠⁠⁠⁠
⁠⁠⁠⁠

node.text:
The @PublicArtFund unveiled yesterday artist Claudia Wieser's "Rehearsal," a set of mixed-media sculptures consisting of ceramic, digital prints, and stainless steel. Find the work in DUMBO, literally down under the Manhattan Bridge overpass in Brooklyn Bridge Park near the intersection of Plymouth and Main streets, where it will remain through April 17, 2022. Link in bio for info.⁠
⁠
Pictured: Claudia Wieser's tile and steel sculptures stand in a grouping, looking like small skyscrapers reminiscent of subway-station walls. The eastern-most tower of the Manhattan Bridge looms in the background. ⁠
⁠
Artwork courtesy Claudia Wieser; Marianne Boesky Gallery New York and Aspen; and Jessica Silverman, San Francisco. Photo by Nicholas Knight, courtesy of Public Art Fund
